Shock Proof

The shell can protect your hard drive, shock and drop, and make your data more stable and safer.

How are ratings calculated?
To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyses reviews to verify trustworthiness.

Mr. Kane
4.0 out of 5 stars Really cheap to buy, although very middling performance
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 28 June 2019
Capacity: S400 120GBColour: Normal SeriesVerified Purchase
I was doing a very cheap, low-end computer build and needed a drive in a hurry so bought this. I bought it for several reasons; firstly - I used to buy these from Chinese websites years ago before Amazon stocked them and I always found them cheap and reliablish.

For this particular build, I needed a drive very quickly and very cheaply. I bought this for around £13.50 and it was delivered the following day. some of the other cheap drives had a couple of days delivery time and I already had a buyer coming to collect this build, so I bought it in installed it straight away.

Physical build quality is good and about the same as all the others in this price bracket. Screw fittings were all good, didn't strip.

The only downside of this is the benchmarking performance getting around 450MB/s read and 320MB/s write. This is definitely towards the bottom end of the performance spectrum, but in actual use, it's hard to tell the difference between this any other SATA drive to be honest.

Would I buy it again? Sure - if I wanted to save £1.50-2.00 on getting a PNY or Lexar or something then I probably would - even though they perform closer to the 550MB/s - 500MB/s rate.

I guess you get what you pay for; the main thing is that I've found them to be reliable and on that basis, I'd buy again and recommend.

TOP 1000 REVIEWER
4.0 out of 5 stars Had no issues yet, Amazing Price.
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 2 February 2020
Capacity: 480GBColour: Normal SeriesVerified Purchase
At the time of purchase i got this SSD for around 25% cheaper than most budget brands and there was only 2 other unknown brands around the same price (£33.59 for 480GB). I picked this one after reading and watching some reviews that pulled the ssd apart and found very good hardware underneath, the reviews also said that they are most likely buying excess/below standard stock and you could buy 2 SSD's, open them both up and find totaly different hardware underneath each one.

So these seem to be a bit pot luck when it comes to speed and longevity but for the price i paid im more than happy with current results, I personaly would not use it as a boot drive or store anything you dont mind losing since i like to buy bigger brands with a higher quality control for anything like that.

But at the time i purchased this nothing really came close in price for this size, i purchased 2 for myself and i gifted one to a friend for christmas. My first one is now my game drive and I have had 0 issues yet after 2-3 months, same with the one i purchased as a gift which is also a game drive and he has had no issues yet.

The second one i purchased was purchased as a media drive and I have not done too much with yet but once again what i have done i have had no problems with.

There is a much bigger chance due to the way these cheap brand source parts and the lower quality control that you are going to have issues with these SSD's. But if you buy it knowing that and use it for non important files just incase your one of the unlucky ones. These are more than half sometimes even a third of the price of the equivalent top tier SSD's like the samsungs and i doubt a normaly user could tell them apart once install in a machine.

I have rated it 4 stars just becuase of the higher chance of failure but for a gaming drive or media drive this is perfect.

5.0 out of 5 stars Transformed an old HP Latptop
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on 24 October 2017
Capacity: 480GBColour: Normal SeriesVerified Purchase
Recently, I have become a fan of KingDian drives. I purchased three smaller drives before I bought the 480GB version. I have also installed one in a relative's PC, & they all work so well that they almost compete with my Samsung SSD's.

I was given a 5 year-old HP Laptop a while back, which had an extremely faulty HDD & wasn't worth the cost of repair to it's owner. It was definitely worth saving, so I set about resurrecting it. For just over £110, I bought & installed another KingDian SSD: this time a 480Gb version. I installed a new copy of Windows 10-64 bit Premium. It works so well that it starts up in less than 10 seconds from entering my password, & all screen icons are booted within another 10 seconds. I installed Crystal Disc Mark & the results were excellent: at least as good as the KingDian SSD's on my mainframe PC.

I now have a great laptop that dramatically out-performs the replacement laptop that my colleague bought! (much to his chagrin). I split the drive to give me a 100GB partition for Windows 10 & programmes, & I have the remainder for a system image & lots of music & photo files. Well worth the effort.

The only suggestion for improvement would be that KingDian could supply some basic cloning & bench-marking software. This would make it a complete package, just as Samsung Magician & Data Migration software does for Samsung drives. It doesn't need to be as sophisticated, but if buyers aren't aware that Crystal Disc Mark & Macrium Reflect freeware are available then it may put them off buying the KingDian drives.

If you have a laptop or PC is limited by a slow HDD (check the Windows Task Manager/ Performance to see if the HDD is maxing out regularly) & would benefit from a performance boost, this could be the answer for a reasonable outlay.
